  "opinion": "As a translator with a PhD background and raised in a family where one parent holds a doctoral degree and the other a vocational diploma, I’ve observed how deeply ingrained stereotypes can affect even those who are well-educated. Stereotype threat in STEM refers to the anxiety that individuals experience when they fear their performance might confirm negative stereotypes about their group. For example, a woman in a physics class might worry that her presence could reinforce the idea that women are less capable in science, leading to decreased focus and poorer performance. This phenomenon isn’t just theoretical—it’s a lived reality for many. Given my own experience as a translator working with diverse academic texts, I’ve seen how these psychological barriers can subtly undermine progress. Addressing stereotype threat is not optional; it requires systemic change. Schools and institutions must implement inclusive curricula that highlight diverse contributions to STEM, ensuring that students from all backgrounds see themselves reflected in the material. Mentorship programs that pair underrepresented students with successful role models can also help alleviate the anxiety associated with these stereotypes. Additionally, training for educators to recognize and mitigate unconscious biases is crucial. My own work in translating academic literature has shown that clear, empathetic communication can bridge gaps between different perspectives. While it’s tempting to think that individual effort alone can solve this issue, the truth is that systemic interventions are necessary. As a man who has navigated both Italian and international academic environments, I understand that the stakes are high—our collective future depends on fostering an environment where everyone feels safe to contribute without fear of judgment.",
